here to the library to look

00:43:24.640 --> 00:43:30.140
at your collection, what would
you tell them to look for?

00:43:31.220 --> 00:43:32.520
&gt;&gt; Connie Regan-Blake: Gosh.

00:43:32.520 --> 00:43:35.440
Well, there's going to be a lot
of photos of the Hicks Family.

00:43:35.440 --> 00:43:37.530
That jumps in my mind.

00:43:37.530 --> 00:43:42.380
And something that I kind of
thought of, I've kept a copy

00:43:42.380 --> 00:43:47.480
of every single promotional
piece of material that we had

00:43:47.480 --> 00:43:51.160
as the folk tellers all the
way through my solo career.

00:43:51.160 --> 00:43:54.730
And I actually thought
about that at one point

00:43:54.730 --> 00:43:58.060
that that might be cool for
someone that is an artist

00:43:58.060 --> 00:44:02.330
or a designer to go back and
just see what is that sheet

00:44:02.330 --> 00:44:06.750
of paper that was
mimeographed with a photograph

00:44:06.750 --> 00:44:08.910
and a few quotes at the bottom

00:44:08.910 --> 00:44:11.210
that Bill Dumler [assumed
spelling] up in Hartford,

00:44:11.210 --> 00:44:13.320
Connecticut helped
us put together.

00:44:13.320 --> 00:44:16.150
In addition to running
that festival up there

00:44:16.150 --> 00:44:21.120
in the coffee house,
he ran a copy company,

00:44:21.120 --> 00:44:22.600
you know, a little shop.

00:44:22.600 --> 00:44:24.180
So, he was literally the one.

00:44:24.180 --> 00:44:28.680
He got Sandy Payton who
had folk legacy records

00:44:28.680 --> 00:44:31.710
to give us a quote because
he had heard us tell stories.

00:44:31.710 --> 00:44:35.690
And what would that be like for
a designer to come in and see

00:44:35.690 --> 00:44:39.910
that first page up to
my business cards now

00:44:39.910 --> 00:44:44.050
that have that, you know,
soft feeling and rounded edges

00:44:44.050 --> 00:44:47.290
and to see that whole
progression.

00:44:47.290 --> 00:44:50.980
So, that's just one tiny way
and certainly storytellers,

00:44:50.980 --> 00:44:54.810
you know, that's what I'm hoping
that people will be inspired

00:44:54.810 --> 00:44:58.360
to tell their own stories
traditional and personal

00:44:58.360 --> 00:45:01.710
and not only necessarily
thinking of it on stage,

00:45:01.710 --> 00:45:04.790
but how can they do that with
their family, how can do they do

00:45:04.790 --> 00:45:06.090
that in their community.

00:45:06.090 --> 00:45:07.570
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: All right.

